WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.580 --> 00:00:05.340
The committee was very interested in progress on this particular issue.

2
00:00:05.420 --> 00:00:09.320
We had a briefing quite some time ago

3
00:00:09.540 --> 00:00:09.800
and

4
00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:13.360
understood that there were some

5
00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:18.180
difficulties, but because of Ministry of Health and

6
00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:22.120
MPI cross involvement

7
00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:24.880
there. If you could

8
00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:29.940
fire away and tell us where we're at, and I'm sure there'll be plenty of questions.

9
00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.850
I can. I should first preface by saying I

10
00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:39.240
prepared some notes that start a bit earlier than that, but I saw your interim

11
00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:39.940
report, and you

12
00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:42.560
obviously know quite a lot about it already.

13
00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:46.020
If I start a reasonable way through the-

14
00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:46.129
Yep

15
00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:46.760
... story,

16
00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:49.810
I may not have too much to say, but-

17
00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:50.850
It's all right.

18
00:00:51.020 --> 00:00:53.240
We may be finished quite quickly. But

19
00:00:55.380 --> 00:00:58.620
just very briefly, as I'm sure you all know, hemp

20
00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:04.240
is a form of cannabis that's got very low THC,

21
00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:04.940
and

22
00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:09.900
THC is the main psychoactive

23
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:11.200
substance. And so

24
00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:14.180
it's

25
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.240
wholly unsuitable as a recreational drug.

26
00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:21.000
But it is nevertheless regulated under the misuse of drugs

27
00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:25.400
legislation, which is why we ended up with

28
00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:25.700
this

29
00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:31.060
review topic. A

30
00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:37.660
year ago when, I think Tim came and talked to you, the

31
00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:39.860
situation was that we had

32
00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:46.190
reasonably comprehensive regulation around a licensing

33
00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:49.780
regime that involved record keeping and monitoring and

34
00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:55.440
reporting obligations and so on. And

35
00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:00.840
when we were briefed about this, our take on it was that

36
00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:04.500
that was a little bit over the top for the risk involved,

37
00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:07.340
which is why we got interested in it as a ministry.

38
00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:12.620
I should say, just very briefly, I'm not sure how across

39
00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:14.300
members are of

40
00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:17.340
the functions of the Ministry of Regulation.

41
00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:19.700
We've got quite a broad range of functions.

42
00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:20.380
But

43
00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:24.640
one of the areas that we work on is reviews of current

44
00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:25.300
legislation.

45
00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:28.860
And that kind of comes in two flavors.

46
00:02:29.540 --> 00:02:30.880
One flavor is that we do

47
00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.640
what we call sector reviews, which are mid-sized reviews of

48
00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:39.350
systems of regulation, like the

49
00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:44.340
regulation around the importation of agricultural and horticultural

50
00:02:44.420 --> 00:02:47.620
products, for example, or solar

51
00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:51.520
panel installation regulation and so on.

52
00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:54.360
And then there's a much smaller limb which is

53
00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:56.480
quite reactive, where we

54
00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:01.220
get tips from the public or from other sources, and we look

55
00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:05.020
at much smaller areas of regulation, and this was in that latter

56
00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:08.200
category. So we'd had intel that

57
00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:12.840
this industry was possibly out regulated, and that's how I got interested in

58
00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:13.000
it.

59
00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:17.760
And we got interested because it looked as if

60
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.860
the industry was underperforming compared to what you might expect.

61
00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:26.080
There were projections for it to grow quite significantly.

62
00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:31.880
Some projections were around the tens of millions of dollars.

63
00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:33.200
Some were around

64
00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.180
much higher than that, although they were possibly a bit optimistic.

65
00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:41.720
And the industry was sitting in the very low millions of

66
00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:45.580
dollars of revenue. And so it looked like something was holding it back.

67
00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.640
And it was possible that it was this regime.

68
00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:54.100
And the regime, we felt, was possibly holding it back in a few ways.

69
00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:54.840
First of all,

70
00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:59.760
although the compliance costs weren't particularly high, they were still a factor.

71
00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:01.680
Secondly,

72
00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:06.880
the need to get a license delays how quickly you can shift

73
00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:08.200
crops and

74
00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:12.920
we had heard anecdotally that there was potential

75
00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:16.459
for a crop failure and for that crop to be quickly

76
00:04:17.601 --> 00:04:20.620
replaced with a hemp crop because it grows quite quickly.

77
00:04:21.579 --> 00:04:25.409
But the time that it took to get a license was standing in the way of that, and

78
00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.140
so land would often

79
00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:31.840
stand unused in that situation instead of being used for

80
00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:34.400
hemp. So that was a second thing.

81
00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:38.940
Thirdly, we had heard that

82
00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:42.780
the restriction on the types of cultivars that could be used was

83
00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:44.720
potentially affecting the

84
00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:48.760
competitiveness of the industry.

85
00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:49.920
And

86
00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:54.720
then there was another set of

87
00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:58.760
issues that I'll come to later that unfortunately we couldn't get into.

88
00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:00.940
But I'll come to those a bit later.

89
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:05.520
So we got interested in it because it looked like there could be a regulatory

90
00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:09.370
solution here, and that's kind of our bread and butter, to try and find things that

91
00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:12.820
are being held up by regulation that we might be able to,

92
00:05:12.920 --> 00:05:15.940
at very low risk, improve.

93
00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:23.680
You commented on the fact that we'd had a bit of trouble with, or there'd been a

94
00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:27.600
bit of trouble with the Ministry of Health and Ministry of

95
00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:28.840
Primary Industries.

96
00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:32.120
That actually wasn't really our experience.

97
00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:36.240
The Ministry of Health was very supportive of the review, because

98
00:05:36.820 --> 00:05:37.140
there were

99
00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:42.040
compliance costs at their end factoring to administer the regime, which they didn't

100
00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:43.740
think was worthwhile.

101
00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:48.780
And so they were pretty supportive the whole way through

102
00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:52.380
and provided a lot of the technical expertise that we didn't have

103
00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.200
in-house around the issues.

104
00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:58.820
MPI did have some concerns, but

105
00:05:58.860 --> 00:06:02.690
the scope of the review was narrowed so that

106
00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:06.548
those concerns weren't-Weren't very much triggered,

107
00:06:06.868 --> 00:06:07.128
and

108
00:06:07.948 --> 00:06:11.808
so they also ended up not being detractors.

109
00:06:12.328 --> 00:06:16.268
So our relationship with both those agencies during the review was actually pretty

110
00:06:16.328 --> 00:06:20.027
good, and they were pretty supportive, certainly in terms of giving technical

111
00:06:20.108 --> 00:06:21.628
expertise where we needed it.

112
00:06:23.808 --> 00:06:27.608
Just to move to the concerns that MPI did have.

113
00:06:28.128 --> 00:06:31.458
So their most major concern was around

114
00:06:32.228 --> 00:06:35.528
the use of hemp in animal feed,

115
00:06:36.668 --> 00:06:40.608
and we didn't include that in the scope of the review,

116
00:06:40.708 --> 00:06:43.048
and that is not being changed.

117
00:06:43.968 --> 00:06:47.088
It is under, as I understand it, constant ongoing

118
00:06:48.628 --> 00:06:52.468
discussion between the industry and MPI to see whether there's some

119
00:06:52.608 --> 00:06:56.588
kind of solution. Because it would be fantastic for the industry if they could

120
00:06:56.648 --> 00:07:00.608
use hemp for animal feed because it would take something

121
00:07:00.648 --> 00:07:04.438
that they have to dispose of at quite a lot of cost and turn it into something

122
00:07:04.608 --> 00:07:05.468
they could sell instead.

123
00:07:07.388 --> 00:07:10.968
But there are real sensitivities in some of our export

124
00:07:11.048 --> 00:07:14.448
markets about any hemp ending up in the

125
00:07:16.108 --> 00:07:17.728
food chain. And so,

126
00:07:19.248 --> 00:07:19.388
the

127
00:07:20.528 --> 00:07:24.048
conclusion is that we would put really big

128
00:07:24.528 --> 00:07:27.628
export industries at risk if we went down that track.

129
00:07:28.268 --> 00:07:31.908
And MPI was very nervous about that, and with

130
00:07:32.128 --> 00:07:35.928
pretty good reason, I think. And I've been on calls between

131
00:07:35.968 --> 00:07:39.568
them and the industry where the industry does appear to

132
00:07:39.628 --> 00:07:43.228
accept that that is a pretty major risk that has to

133
00:07:43.248 --> 00:07:45.047
be carefully navigated.

134
00:07:46.808 --> 00:07:50.248
So that put a review of the ACVM

135
00:07:50.608 --> 00:07:52.508
legislation out of scope of our review.

136
00:07:54.068 --> 00:07:57.988
It did remain a small concern for MPI because they were worried that,

137
00:07:58.668 --> 00:08:01.328
if there was a proliferation of people growing

138
00:08:02.228 --> 00:08:05.988
hemp, that some people might just feed it to animals anyway.

139
00:08:07.168 --> 00:08:11.048
And the way that we dealt with that was that anybody who

140
00:08:11.088 --> 00:08:12.928
wants to grow industrial hemp,

141
00:08:14.028 --> 00:08:17.408
going forward, I'm probably getting a little bit ahead of myself because I'll talk

142
00:08:17.448 --> 00:08:21.268
about where the review got to, but just to finish the point, going forward,

143
00:08:22.228 --> 00:08:26.188
will have to notify MPI before they plant, which will give MPI

144
00:08:26.228 --> 00:08:29.988
the opportunity to reach out to them and stress the

145
00:08:30.008 --> 00:08:31.448
importance of

146
00:08:32.369 --> 00:08:34.768
the hemp not getting close to animals that

147
00:08:35.749 --> 00:08:38.288
might end up in the export food chain.

148
00:08:39.989 --> 00:08:41.009
Oh, sorry, did you have a question?

149
00:08:41.068 --> 00:08:44.948
But that notification is not the same as them requiring to get a license directly

150
00:08:44.988 --> 00:08:48.908
from MPI. Just a notification. Just a notification. Okay. That's right.

151
00:08:49.188 --> 00:08:49.548
Yep.

152
00:08:51.028 --> 00:08:54.568
So where we got to on our recommendations in the end was that we

153
00:08:54.628 --> 00:08:58.188
recommended that the license regime be removed

154
00:08:58.928 --> 00:08:59.928
entirely really.

155
00:09:01.168 --> 00:09:04.448
So that got rid of the record-keeping

156
00:09:04.488 --> 00:09:07.188
obligations and reporting obligations and so on,

157
00:09:08.908 --> 00:09:11.248
and meant that the people could be more nimble.

158
00:09:13.328 --> 00:09:15.508
There are a few restrictions that remain in place.

159
00:09:15.628 --> 00:09:18.848
So you still need a license to import or export.

160
00:09:19.848 --> 00:09:22.068
There are restrictions on what you can do with the plant.

161
00:09:22.128 --> 00:09:25.588
So this is really the deregulation's really around the

162
00:09:26.348 --> 00:09:26.928
stalks,

163
00:09:28.928 --> 00:09:30.428
and the seeds.

164
00:09:32.468 --> 00:09:36.368
So if people want to use the leaves

165
00:09:36.408 --> 00:09:38.528
and flowers, they really need to sell them into a

166
00:09:40.868 --> 00:09:43.108
licensed medicinal cannabis scheme.

167
00:09:44.348 --> 00:09:47.248
Because that's where the cannabinoids are.

168
00:09:51.088 --> 00:09:53.028
There was an old restriction under the

169
00:09:54.188 --> 00:09:54.888
old regime,

170
00:09:56.068 --> 00:09:59.788
separate from the license, which said that industrial hemp growers could

171
00:09:59.888 --> 00:10:03.748
only sell a limited number of plants and seeds to

172
00:10:04.568 --> 00:10:08.448
medicinal cannabis schemes. We saw

173
00:10:08.508 --> 00:10:10.328
no reason for that, so we removed that as well.

174
00:10:10.428 --> 00:10:14.348
So they at least can sell unlimited amounts into those medicinal cannabis

175
00:10:14.388 --> 00:10:15.848
schemes after the change.

176
00:10:18.288 --> 00:10:21.408
There is also still the restriction that I talked about around

177
00:10:22.128 --> 00:10:22.748
animal feed.

178
00:10:24.668 --> 00:10:28.648
And we introduced a new requirement, which was to

179
00:10:28.668 --> 00:10:32.608
replace the licensing, which was that before anybody planted,

180
00:10:33.168 --> 00:10:37.048
they needed to notify both the police and MPI.

181
00:10:38.188 --> 00:10:41.308
The MPI bit was so that MPI could do its outreach.

182
00:10:42.728 --> 00:10:46.488
The police bit was because there was a concern that

183
00:10:47.728 --> 00:10:50.488
criminal interests might see this as an opportunity to

184
00:10:52.428 --> 00:10:56.128
piggyback on a growing industry and potentially use it as a

185
00:10:57.028 --> 00:10:59.828
money-laundering operation that could also

186
00:11:01.108 --> 00:11:04.248
disguise an illicit cannabis growing operation.

187
00:11:04.428 --> 00:11:08.228
That was kind of the concern. And so the requirement to

188
00:11:08.268 --> 00:11:12.008
notify police before you plant was intended as a deterrent for that

189
00:11:12.408 --> 00:11:12.908
largely.

190
00:11:13.988 --> 00:11:17.808
And if that did start happening as a source of intel for the police.

191
00:11:19.508 --> 00:11:22.828
So that was a slightly new thing. There was

192
00:11:23.048 --> 00:11:26.868
previously a notification requirement, but it was a bit loose

193
00:11:26.908 --> 00:11:28.688
because it was after planting,

194
00:11:29.588 --> 00:11:31.948
and within a kind of reasonable period of time.

195
00:11:32.508 --> 00:11:36.448
Whereas we replaced that with the requirement that the notification had

196
00:11:36.488 --> 00:11:40.068
to be before planting and annually updated,

197
00:11:40.768 --> 00:11:41.288
so that

198
00:11:42.148 --> 00:11:46.068
if police found any plants on any property and there wasn't

199
00:11:46.088 --> 00:11:49.948
a notification in place that was less than a year old, then they

200
00:11:49.968 --> 00:11:51.488
could deem that to be illicit cannabis.

201
00:11:51.608 --> 00:11:55.528
So that was kind of our bright-line way of trying

202
00:11:55.568 --> 00:11:56.228
to deter

203
00:11:57.028 --> 00:11:59.508
the criminal elements from getting involved.

204
00:12:01.288 --> 00:12:04.148
The recommendations of the review were accepted,

205
00:12:04.268 --> 00:12:07.060
umComplete by

206
00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:10.320
Cabinet and the

207
00:12:11.640 --> 00:12:14.960
new secondary legislation to bring it into effect has been

208
00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:18.800
promulgated, but we're within the 28 days before it becomes

209
00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:22.700
effective. So the new regime is not yet effective but will be

210
00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:23.940
very soon.

211
00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:28.080
So that's really all I have by way of update.

212
00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:31.910
And I probably can't string it out too much more.

213
00:12:32.540 --> 00:12:35.120
Does anybody on the committee have any questions?

214
00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:40.380
So it can be affected by an order in council without any

215
00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:44.800
legislative change. But what about the Misuse of Drugs Act stuff?

216
00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:45.280
So the

217
00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:50.400
Misuse of Drugs Acts contemplates that you can

218
00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:54.340
permit certain uses of the cannabis plant through regulations,

219
00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.900
and so this can all be done through regulations.

220
00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:57.360
Mm.

221
00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:59.780
And so the regulations are permissive of

222
00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:04.160
industrial hemp being grown,

223
00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:09.540
distributed, sold, basically used in any way apart from the

224
00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:13.420
restrictions that I talked about before, which largely relate to the

225
00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:14.540
flowers and leaves-

226
00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:15.440
Mm

227
00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:19.190
... and use for animal feed, which is in a different set of

228
00:13:19.220 --> 00:13:19.980
legislation.

229
00:13:21.420 --> 00:13:24.900
So I'm still not clear about the Misuse of Drugs Act bit of it.

230
00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:26.700
So the Misuse of Drugs Act,

231
00:13:29.140 --> 00:13:33.000
prevents you from doing a whole lot of things with cannabis because it's a

232
00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:33.960
class C drug.

233
00:13:34.260 --> 00:13:34.300
Mm.

234
00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:36.740
But it allows regulations to be passed-

235
00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:37.250
Right. Okay

236
00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:38.880
... that allow you to do things.

237
00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:39.230
Right.

238
00:13:39.290 --> 00:13:43.080
And the regulations allow this. So we already had regula-

239
00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:46.980
since 2006, we've had regulations that have allowed some use of

240
00:13:47.020 --> 00:13:47.760
industrial hemp.

241
00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:48.340
Right.

242
00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:52.020
It's just that they came with a whole lot of conditions attached, and we were kind

243
00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:54.560
of stripping away those conditions.

244
00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:55.600
And one final one.

245
00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:56.180
Okay.

246
00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:57.500
How does the industry feel about it?

247
00:13:58.820 --> 00:13:58.830
The industry.

248
00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:03.080
So in the early consultation, the industry was a little bit

249
00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:03.800
split about it.

250
00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:05.840
But we ended up

251
00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:10.920
mainly talking to a few representatives who have become very positive about

252
00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:12.280
it over time. The

253
00:14:14.519 --> 00:14:17.860
industry's view on it is a little bit split depending on the type of business they

254
00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:19.880
have. So exporters

255
00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:24.080
saw some benefit in a licensing regime

256
00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:26.280
because it gave a

257
00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:31.180
government stamp of approval to the product that they were exporting, and

258
00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:34.080
so that they had some kind of attachment to it.

259
00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:38.660
But we didn't really hear that loudly all the way through.

260
00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:41.990
So even the people who had that interest kind of said, "Oh, no, we do support the

261
00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:42.649
changes," but

